{{Infobox website | name = The Arts Desk | logo = Tad-logo-red.gif | commercial = Yes | type = Journalism | registration = Yes | language = English | url = {{URL|www.theartsdesk.com}} }}
'''The Arts Desk''' ('''theartsdesk.com''') is a British [[arts journalism]] website containing [[review]]s, [[interview]]s, news and other content related to [[music]], [[theatre]], [[television]], [[film]]s and other art forms written by journalists from a variety of traditional and web-based publications.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/the-25-best-music-websites-1803346.html?action=gallery&ino=21|title= The Arts Desk|newspaper= [[The Independent]]|date=16 October 2009|accessdate= 9 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartsdesk.com/about|title=The Arts Desk|publisher=}}</ref>
It launched in September 2009 as a shareholder collective. Its honorary chairman 2010–2013 was Sir [[John Tusa]], former managing director of the BBC World Service and Barbican Arts Centre.
In 2012, it won an Online Media Award as the best specialist journalism site jointly with the website for ''[[The Economist]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlinemediaawards.net/archive/2012/|title=Online Media Awards|publisher=}}</ref>
Notable contributors include [[Aleks Sierz]], Jasper Rees, Matt Wolf, Ismene Brown, [[Joe Muggs]], Tom Birchenough, David Nice, Kieron Tyler and Alexandra Coghlan.
